&lt;h3 id=&#34;detailed-method&#34; &gt;Detailed Method
&lt;span&gt;
    &lt;a href=&#34;#detailed-method&#34;&gt;
        &lt;svg viewBox=&#34;0 0 28 23&#34; height=&#34;100%&#34; width=&#34;19&#34; xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/2000/svg&#34;&gt;&lt;path d=&#34;M10 13a5 5 0 0 0 7.54.54l3-3a5 5 0 0 0-7.07-7.07l-1.72 1.71&#34; fill=&#34;none&#34; stroke-linecap=&#34;round&#34; stroke-miterlimit=&#34;10&#34; stroke-width=&#34;2&#34;/&gt;&lt;path d=&#34;M14 11a5 5 0 0 0-7.54-.54l-3 3a5 5 0 0 0 7.07 7.07l1.71-1.71&#34; fill=&#34;none&#34; stroke-linecap=&#34;round&#34; stroke-miterlimit=&#34;10&#34; stroke-width=&#34;2&#34;/&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;
    &lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you need to use it globally, you need to put &amp;ldquo;config.toml, config.yaml, or config.json&amp;rdquo; in the root directory of the website (according to the specific situation, my file is config.toml, so the following code is also modified by the .toml file For example. For the modification method of other files, please refer to the content in the Inline Shortcodes link above) Add two lines of code to the file:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34;&gt;&lt;code&gt;enableInlineShortcodes = true
enableEmoji = true
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this way, emoji can be used directly in the website. After entering the code corresponding to emoji, the effect is as follows:&lt;/p&gt;
